         <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>You are exactely right. If I had been living in the days before Christopher Columbus, the common belief that the world was flat would have been a major conflict with the Bible, which states that the world is a sphere. Hundreds of years later, logic and reason is used again to prove that the world is a sphere, thus validating the Bible. <hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote><BR>Don't forget that the bible has most likely had many alterations through the years. A big drawback to following something like the bible is the possibility of human interference in its ideas. <BR>For all you know there may have never been any mention in the bible of the shape of the world until it was figured out, then all you have to do is put it in there, let simmer for a few hundred years, and viola, one idea that's been in the bible for hundreds of years, yes even back before science figured it out. <BR>After time passes, people forget some things such as the addition of a verse or two into the bible. While this sort of thing couldn't happen nowadays, it was a very real situation about 600 years ago when saying something negative about the church meant very bad consequences.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>How many times has reason and logic been wrong over the centuries?<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote><BR>And how many times has it been right, leading to a new invention, idea, or even new way of understanding? I'd say enough to want to continue to use it as a method of deciphering our universe. </P><P>Are you aware that a scientific theory is designed so that it can be disproved? The point of that is to be able to easily disprove a theory if you find evidence that disproves it, that is pretty much the center of the scientific method. The bible is designed so that it cannot be disproven no matter how much evidence there is to disprove it. The fact that it's near impossible to disprove is its greatest weakness in the eye of science.</P><P>Example?<BR>Einstein's relativity theories. Lots of people went to their grave not believing a word of it, but as time progressed one experiment after another has shown that he was right. But it is still very fallible, if it is ever disproven then so it will be, and people will be invited to either try and discredit the new theory or do experiments to validate it. If you use the scientific method on a biblical theory, good luck trying to disprove it, no matter how much evidence you have against a biblical theory there will always be people who will think that the evidence doesn't matter. </P><P>Yes I know that science cannot discredit every single theory presented by the bible, but the bible also has a lot of discrepancies with scientific evidence.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>I want every law-abiding citizen to have the right to carry a concealed weapon.<BR>Women should have the right to get an abortion.<BR>I don’t like the government passing death sentences, I prefer death by aging.<BR>If I’m terminally ill I should the right to end my life with dignity.<BR>I like the fact that there is a separation of religion and state.<BR>I think tobacco should be banned (I smoke, btw.) and marijuana should be legally obtainable and usable.<BR>I’d like a flat tax, one with no deductions.<BR>I like my privacy. I want my personal information protected.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Well put, except for the tobacco thing, if people want to excercise their freedom of choice and smoke their lungs out, then more power to them, I'll use my freedom of choice and not smoke.</P><P>Here is a link to the full text of our constitution -</P><P><a href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/constitution.table.html" target="_blank">http://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/constitution.table.html</a></P><P>The first amendment of the constitution has this to say about religion:</P><P>Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the Government for a redress of grievances.</P><P>There is no clause anywhere in our constitution that says separation of church and state. Look it over, if I missed something and I'm wrong then please correct me, I don't want to run around spouting things that aren't true. From what I read, the only thing the constitution has to say about religion is that congress cannot make any laws that interfere with the operation of the church.</P><P>Mcren<BR>Vallon Zek<BR>51st level necromancer</P><P><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=82694" target="_blank">http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=82694</a></P><P></P><P>Edited for grammar and neatness by - Mcren on 06/29/2002  10:07:43</P><P>Edited by - Mcren on 06/29/2002  10:08:34<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
